  "cycles": [
    {
      "num": 1,
      "name": "Rebuild & Reset",
      "tagline": "Re-load What You've Lost",
      "weeks": "Weeks 1–5",
      "focuses": [
        "Progressively re-load the injured right lat and rotator cuff while correcting left-right asymmetry.",
        "Establish baseline hypertrophy and movement quality across all major patterns."
      ]
    },
    {
      "num": 2,
      "name": "Symmetry Engine",
      "weeks": "Weeks 6–10",
      "focuses": [
        "Drive unilateral hypertrophy to close the strength and size gap between sides.",
        "Reintroduce graded overhead loading as shoulder tolerance returns."
      ],
      "message": {
        "paragraphs": [
          "Rebuild & Reset did exactly what it promised: your bench climbed 20 to 28 kg, your rows kept pace, and — the one that matters — the lat you messaged about is officially back. Symmetry Engine is where the rebuild becomes an upgrade: five weeks of driving the left side until it stops being the weaker side, while overhead pressing and real pulling return to your program on a graded ramp.",
          "Your mental job this cycle is restraint in two places: the new lifts start deliberately easy and earn one RPE point per pain-free week — don't rush the ramp — and the left still leads every unilateral rep, setting the ceiling the right must match. By week 5 you should be pressing overhead standing, pulling from a full stretch without a second thought, and moving loads on one leg you used to need two for."
        ],
        "outcomes": [
          "Lat Pulldown built from RPE 6 to 8 — pain-free, full range",
          "Standing overhead press back in the program, full stack lockout",
          "Front-foot-elevated split squat up 2–4 kg with the left leading",
          "Dumbbell bench at 30 kg total",
          "Left side matching the right at equal loads on every unilateral lift"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "num": 3,
      "name": "Armour Build",
      "weeks": "Weeks 11–15",
      "focuses": [
        "Accumulate maximum lean mass through intensified hypertrophy across the whole body.",
        "Build shoulder girdle durability with loaded carries, heavy rows, and controlled overhead work."
      ],
      "teaser": {
        "paragraphs": [
          "Symmetry Engine hands you a body with no weak side and no protected lifts — and that's exactly when we start building serious size on top of it. Cycle 3 is the heaviest, hungriest block of the whole roadmap: maximum lean mass, a shoulder girdle built like armour, and the kind of frame that doesn't fade in a third set. Every balanced rep you bank now is a brick in that build.",
          "First we made you symmetrical. Next we make you bigger than you've ever been."
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "num": 4,
      "name": "Power Translation",
      "weeks": "Weeks 16–20",
      "focuses": [
        "Convert new muscle into tennis-specific rotational power and serve-chain speed.",
        "Maintain strength while introducing medicine ball, plyometric, and landmine rotational work."
      ]
    },
    {
      "num": 5,
      "name": "Match Engine",
      "weeks": "Weeks 21–25",
      "focuses": [
        "Build repeat-effort capacity so performance quality holds through long matches and tournament weeks.",
        "Preserve the strength and mass gained while tapering into competition-ready form."
      ]
    }
  ],
