  "notes": {
    "greeting": "For You, Lemuel",
    "cards": [
      {
        "icon": "🪢",
        "title": "Your Lat Is Back — Ramp It Right",
        "body": "You asked to pull properly again, and this cycle grants it — on a ramp. Lat Pulldown starts at RPE 6 in week one and earns exactly one RPE point per pain-free week, up to 8. That's not caution for caution's sake: tissue that just finished rebuilding adapts brilliantly to graded load and badly to a hero week. If anything sharp or stabbing shows up mid-set — not a stretch, not fatigue, sharp — end the set, drop the load 30%, and message Amir the same day."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🩺",
        "title": "The Cuff Hasn't Signed Off Yet",
        "body": "Your lat is declared healthy; your right cuff isn't yet — the \"inflames quickly\" notes stopped in early June, but stopped isn't the same as cleared. So the standing dumbbell press follows the same graded ramp (RPE 6, +1 per clean week), and the half-kneeling landmine press stays on the bench as your instant fallback. Any pinch at any point in the press — drop back to the landmine that session and tell Amir. The cuff prep block stays non-negotiable, every upper day, even when you're rushed."
      },
      {
        "icon": "⬅️",
        "title": "Left Leads, Right Matches — Still",
        "body": "This is the Symmetry cycle, and the rule that built it doesn't retire: every unilateral lift — split squats, step-ups, hip thrusts, calf raises, single-arm rows — starts left, and whatever the left does at the prescribed RPE is the ceiling for the right. The app can't measure your asymmetry for us, so you're the sensor: when the left lags on reps or the right feels insultingly easy, write it in the day notes. That one line of feedback is how we know when the gap is actually closed instead of just quiet."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🎾",
        "title": "The Squeezed-Week Protocol",
        "body": "Twice last cycle you compressed four sessions into two days at single sets when coaching and tournaments blew up your week — good instinct, so now it's official programming. When a week collapses: run two combined sessions (Day 1+2 together, Day 3+4 together) at 1–2 sets per exercise, cuff prep included, everything else at normal loads. That's a planned maintenance week, not a failure — no guilt, no doubling up next week to \"make it back.\" The court is your sport; the gym flexes around it."
      },
      {
        "icon": "⚖️",
        "title": "Your Fatigue Comes From the Court",
        "body": "Your readiness data says the program isn't what tires you — the 2–5 hours a day of training and coaching is. So use the levers built in for exactly that: on a low-readiness morning drop every RPE by one, and if time or energy only allows one thing, do the day's first primary lift plus the cuff prep — that's the minimum effective dose and it genuinely counts. A trimmed session logged beats a perfect session skipped, every single week of this cycle."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🍽️",
        "title": "Eat Like Armour Build Is Coming",
        "body": "Next cycle is the mass block, and it will only work if the eating habit already exists when it arrives. Keep the Cycle 1 baseline running: a palm of protein four times a day, carbs placed around tennis and lifting, never training fasted — and weigh yourself once a week, same morning, same conditions, and log it in your check-in. We don't currently have your weight trend in the data, and for the next two cycles that number matters as much as any load in the app."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🚦",
        "title": "Your In-Gym Pain Rules",
        "body": "With a freshly-cleared lat and a cuff still on probation, you need one clear rulebook mid-session. OK — muscle burn, effort fatigue, next-day stiffness: that's training, keep going. Not OK — sharp pain, anything radiating down the arm, numbness or tingling, or pain that builds through a set instead of staying flat. The ladder: mild and fading → finish the set and write it in the day note. Building, or it changes how you move → stop that exercise, switch to its fallback (landmine for the press, straight-arm pulldown for the lat pulldown), and message Amir. Sharp, radiating, numb, or unfamiliar → end the session and message Amir before you train again. This isn't caution theatre — it's how the right lat and cuff stay cleared."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🛌",
        "title": "Sleep Is Still the Multiplier",
        "body": "Your 7–8 hours at genuinely good quality is why this program can ask for progression in the same weeks you're coaching daily — it's your biggest recovery asset and it costs nothing. Protect it on tournament weeks especially, when the schedule tempts you to trade it for travel and late matches. The hierarchy when life squeezes: sleep stays, then the squeezed-week protocol handles the gym. Never sacrifice the first to protect the second."
      }
    ]
  }
